{"title_page": "2004 in Singapore", "text_new": "{{Dynamic list}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Year in Singapore|2004}}\n\nThe following lists events that happened during '''[[2004]] in [[Singapore]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[President of Singapore|President]]: [[S.R. Nathan]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Obituary: Sellapan Ramanathan (SR Nathan), statesman|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/obituary-sellapan-ramanathan-sr-nathan-statesman-1-4225292|website=Scotsman|accessdate=29 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]]: [[Goh Chok Tong]] (until 12 August), [[Lee Hsien Loong]] (starting 12 August)<ref name=nas>{{cite web|title=Changeover of Prime Minister: President's Office Press Statement, 10August 2004|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=2004081001.htm|website=www.nas.gov.sg|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n*1 January - The [[Goods and Services Tax (Singapore)|Goods and Services Tax]] is raised from 4% to 5%.<ref>{{cite web |title=Introduction of the Goods and Services Tax |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/c5594d45-4948-4080-a6fb-5175eb8d83c3 |publisher=NLB |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n*3 January - The [[Millennia Institute]] is established from a merger of other Centralised Institutes.\n*8 January - The [[Infocomm Development Authority of Singapore]] announced that phone numbers starting with '8' will become available from April after high demand for phone numbers starting with '9'.<ref>{{cite web |title=10 million mobile nos with prefix '8' launch |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20040109-1.2.6.6 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=10 September 2019 |date=9 January 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Supercharging Singapore: The 2000s|url=https://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/2015/10/35-years-of-ict/supercharging-singapore/the-2000s.html|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*3 February - The Braddell Flyover is opened to traffic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Braddell Flyover opens today (Page 3) |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes20040203-1.1.19 |publisher=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=3 February 2004}}</ref>\n*12 February - The [[Carlsberg Sky Tower]] (renamed to Tiger Sky Tower) is opened.\n*22 February - Plans for a new hospital in Jurong were postponed in favour for one in the north. These plans were elaborated on 22 March, when the [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Health Ministry]] announced a Northern General Hospital (now [[Khoo Teck Puat Hospital]]) in Yishun.<ref>{{cite web |title=Next new hospital to be in the north |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes20040223-1.1.6 |publisher=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=23 February 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=400-bed hospital for the north in Yishun Central |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes20040323-1.1.4 |publisher=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=23 March 2004}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n*9 March - The [[Singapore Tourism Board]] launched a new tourism campaign called Uniquely Singapore.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Uniquely Singapore\" tourism campaign is launched|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/a016f18a-d260-4078-913d-93b58528b87f#1|website=NLB|accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref> \n*13 March - A new pre-tertiary arts school (now [[School of the Arts, Singapore|School of the Arts]]) is announced during a parliamentary debate to cater for students between the ages of 13 to 18.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ministerial Statement by Minister Lee Boon Yang in Parliament: Announcement on The Arts School |url=https://www.mci.gov.sg/pressroom/news-and-stories/pressroom/2004/3/ministerial-statement-by-minister-lee-boon-yang-in-parliamentannouncement-on-the-arts-school |website=MITA (now MCI) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=13 March 2004}}</ref> \n*17 March - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced more flexibility for school admissions and an all-rounded school ranking system.<ref>{{cite web |title=Greater flexibility in the school admission system |url=http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040317b.htm |website=MOE |accessdate=23 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308131150/http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040317b.htm |archivedate=8 March 2013 |date=17 March 2004 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=A more broad-based school ranking system |url=http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040317a.htm |website=MOE |accessdate=23 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308131557/http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040317a.htm |archivedate=8 March 2013 |date=17 March 2004 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*18 March - \n**The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced that the EM1 and EM2 streams will be merged.<ref>{{cite web |title=Refinements to primary school streaming |url=http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040318.htm |website=MOE |accessdate=23 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308131114/http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040318.htm |archivedate=8 March 2013 |date=18 March 2004 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n**The [[chewing gum ban in Singapore|chewing gum ban]] is partially lifted with the launch of [[Nicorette]], a smoking cessation gum.<ref>{{cite news |title=12-year chewing gum ban partially lifted |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20040317-2.2.13.5 |accessdate=23 August 2019 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |date=17 March 2004}}</ref>\n*26 March - [[The Arts House]] is opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening of The Arts House |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/39c23dc2-b6b6-416e-814b-ba558864bce5 |website=NLB |accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n*23 March - The [[Immigration and Checkpoints Authority]]'s Coastal Command Headquarters on [[Pulau Brani]] is officially opened by then [[Ministry of Home Affairs (Singapore)|Minister for Home Affairs]] [[Wong Kan Seng]].\n*29 March - The [[Media censorship in Singapore|M18 and R21 ratings]] are introduced, among other changes.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Film Rating System Offers More Viewing Choices |url=https://www2.imda.gov.sg/news-and-events/Media-Room/archived/mda/Media-Releases/2004/new-film-rating-system-offers-more-viewing-choices |website=MDA (now IMDA) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=22 March 2004}}</ref>\n*31 March - The [[Old National Library Building]] at Fort Canning is closed for the building of [[Fort Canning Tunnel]].\n\n===April===\n*1 April - \n**Two statutory boards, the [[Accounting and Corporate Regulatory Authority]] and [[Singapore Examinations and Assessment Board]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Formation of Singapore Examinations & Assessment Board|url=http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040331.htm |website=MOE |date=31 March 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025204603/http://moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040331.htm |archivedate=25 October 2012}}</ref> are formed.\n**All hawker centres are now managed by the [[National Environment Agency]], taking over roles previously held by the [[Housing and Development Board]] and [[JTC Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hawker centres |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1637_2010-01-31.html |website=NLB |accessdate=6 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 2 April - The [[Singapore Sports School]] is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening of the Singapore Sports School |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=2004040202.htm |website=NAS |accessdate=28 July 2019 |date=2 April 2004}}</ref>\n* 20 April \u2013 A section of [[Nicoll Highway]] [[Nicoll Highway collapse|collapsed]], four workers were killed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Loh |first1=Sharon |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20040421.2.2 |title=MRT worksite collapse wrecks Nicoll Highway |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |access-date=8 November 2019 |date=21 April 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Friday\u2019s fatal mishap among worst worksite accidents since 2004 Nicoll Highway tragedy|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/fridays-fatal-mishap-worst-worksite-accident-2004-nicoll-highway-tragedy|website=TODAYonline|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n*1 May - \n**The [[National Trades Union Congress]]'s new headquarters, [[One Marina Boulevard]] is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening of One Marina Boulevard |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=2004050101.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=22 August 2019 |date=1 April 2004}}</ref>\n**[[Singapore Pools]] is transferred to the [[Singapore Totalisator Board]]; present-day Tote Board (a statutory board of the [[Ministry of Finance (Singapore)|Ministry of Finance]]), taking over this role from [[Temasek Holdings]].\n*4 May - \n**The first $10 polymer notes are released.<ref>{{cite web|title=MAS Issues $10 Polymer Portrait Notes|url=https://www.mas.gov.sg/news/media-releases/2004/mas-issues-10dollar-polymer-portrait-notes|website=MAS|accessdate=15 July 2019}}</ref>\n**[[Valuair]] launches its first flights.\n*14 May - The [[Media Development Authority]] (MDA) awards the 99.5FM frequency to [[MediaCorp]] under MediaCorp Radio. The new station, GROOVES 99.5FM (renamed [[Lush 99.5FM]]) will broadcast local music and arts programmes, as well as jazz and programmes by tertiary students. The station will start broadcasting by end 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.imda.gov.sg/news-and-events/Media-Room/archived/mda/Media-Releases/2004/mediacorp-radio-awarded-995fm-frequency-for-new-radio-station |title=MediaCorp Radio Awarded 99.5FM Frequency For New Radio Station |website=MDA (now IMDA) |date=14 May 2004 |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n*19 May \u2013 First Lieutenant Brandon Loo of the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force]] is killed when his F-16 jet crashed while on training from the [[Luke Air Force Base]] in [[Arizona]].\n*21 May - The [[Changi Naval Base]] was officially opened.\n*29 May - [[StarHub]] launches its new digital cable TV service.<ref>{{cite web |title=Digital Cable Launch of Starhub Cable Vision Ltd |url=https://www.mci.gov.sg/pressroom/news-and-stories/pressroom/2004/5/speech-by-minister-lee-boon-yang-at-the-digital-cable-launch-of-starhub-cable-vision-ltd-at-2d-ayer-rajah-crescent-aos-building |publisher=MITA (now MCI) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=29 May 2004}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n*1 June - Security guards are now deployed in [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|MRT]] stations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Security guards start MRT patrols |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20040601-1.2.8.4 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=2 May 2020 |date=1 June 2004}}</ref>\n*4 June - Hippo City Sightseeing bus in Singapore started operations.\n*5 June - [[Wild Wild Wet]], a [[water theme park]] opens to the public in [[NTUC Downtown East|Downtown East]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Wild Wild Wet opens in Downtown East|url=http://getforme.com/previous2004/previous200604_wildwildwetopensindowntowneast.htm|website=Get For Me (Singapore)|accessdate=8 August 2019}}</ref>\n*15 June - [[Ministry of Defence (Singapore)|MINDEF]] announced that [[National service in Singapore|National Service]] will be cut from 2.5 years to 2 years from the December 2004 batch.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ministerial Statement on Full-time National Service Duration|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/MINDEF_20040615002.pdf|website=NAS|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref> \n*18 June - The third [[NEWater]] plant opened in [[Seletar]]. It operated for seven years until its closure in 2011. \n*29 June - A power blackout occurred in Singapore, affecting about one-third residents of Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=Massive blackout hits many parts of Singapore |url=http://getforme.com/previous2004/previous300604_massiveblackouthitsmanypartsofsingapore.htm |website=Getforme Singapore |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=30 June 2004}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n*20 July - The National Security Secretariat was renamed to [[National Security Coordination Secretariat]] as part of an enhanced [[national security]] plan.\n\n===August===\n*12 August - [[Lee Hsien Loong]] was sworn as the third [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20040813-1.2.2 |title=Let us shape our future together |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |access-date=12 February 2020 |date=13 August 2004}}</ref>\n*22 August - Pro-family policies were introduced during the [[Singapore National Day Rally|National Day Rally]]. Among the measures include an enhanced [[Baby bonus#Singapore|Baby Bonus]] scheme, increased maternity leave, more childcare options, a five-day work week, among others. In addition, female civil servants can claim medical benefits for their dependant unmarried children below 18 year and spouses from 1 January 2005, as well as two-day childcare leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=2004082502.htm|title=New package of measures to support parenthood|website=NAS|accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=2004082596.htm|title=\nCivil Service moves ahead with changes to promote a pro-family environment and better work-life balance for civil servants|website=NAS|accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n* 2 September - The [[Media Development Authority]] allows the sale of [[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]], a women-oriented magazine, coming after a 22-year ban since 1982 on the grounds of nudity. However, the magazine will be shrink-wrapped with the label 'Unsuitable for the Young' to protect vulnerable consumers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.imda.gov.sg/news-and-events/Media-Room/archived/mda/Media-Releases/2004/cosmopolitan-to-be-available-from-this-month|title=Cosmopolitan to be available from this month|publisher=MDA (now IMDA)|access-date=28 August 2019|date=2 September 2004}}</ref>\n* 17 September - In a bid to stem losses, [[MediaCorp]] and [[Singapore Press Holdings]] (SPH) announced the [[Singapore media merger of 2004|merging]] of their media operations. A new holding company [[MediaCorp TV]] will be created with MediaCorp owning 80 percent and SPH holding the remaining 20 percent. In addition, MediaCorp Press will continue to be owned by MediaCorp; holding a 60 percent stake with 40 percent to be sold to SPH. [[Channel i (Singapore)|Channel i]] will be reviewed for commercial viability while [[Streats]] will be merged with [[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sph.com.sg/media_releases/150 |title=MediaCorp And Singapore Press Holdings Merge Their TV And Free Newspaper Operations |website=MediaCorp, SPH |access-date=5 August 2019 |date=17 September 2004}}</ref> \n* 23 September - [[VivoCity]], formerly known as the HarbourFront Mall, is unveiled, opening in December 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mapletree.com.sg/en/Media/News/2004/Sept/23092004-MapletreeUnveilsNewWaveRetail.aspx|title=Mapletree Unveils the New Wave Of Retail|publisher=Mapletree|access-date=29 July 2019|date=23 September 2004}}</ref>\n* 24 September - The [[Direct School Admission]] was announced, allowing Primary 6 and Secondary 4 students to be guaranteed a place in a [[Secondary education in Singapore|secondary school]] and [[Junior college (Singapore)|junior college]] of their choice respectively. The scheme took effect from the 2005 cohort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/PR24Sep04.pdf|title=\nDirect School Admission for Integrated Programme|publisher=NAS|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 26 September - Reviews were announced for education awards, new school achievement tables and the scrapping of rankings for IP schools and junior colleges.<ref>{{cite news |title=A Broader Picture of Schools' Performance in Academic and Non-Academic Domains |url=http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040924b.htm |accessdate=28 July 2019 |publisher=MOE |date=26 September 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423085655/http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040924b.htm |archivedate=23 April 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 30 September - [[PSA International]] sells its stake in CWT, a logistics company.<ref>{{cite news |title=PSA to sell entire stake in logistics company CWT (Page 38) |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/today20041001-1.1.38 |accessdate=23 August 2019 |publisher=Today (retrieved from NLB) |date=1 October 2004}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n* 2 October - The [[Yellow Ribbon Project]] and Yellow Ribbon Fund are officially launched to give ex-convicts a second chance.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yellow Ribbon Project |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1402_2009-01-05.html |website=NLB |accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tie a yellow ribbon... |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20041004-1.2.51.11 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=4 October 2004}}</ref>\n* 29 October - The first units of [[The Sail @ Marina Bay]] are launched, which is jointly developed by City Developments Limited and AIG Global Real Estate.<ref>{{cite web |title=CDL Celebrates the Launch of The Sail @ Marina Bay With a Big Bang |url=http://ir.cdl.com.sg/static-files/079893ec-2c5b-463f-aaf1-47d11f7b82e2 |publisher=CDL |accessdate=23 August 2019 |date=29 October 2004}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n* 29 November - The [[Changi Air Base (East)]] is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web|title=RADM (NS) Teo Chee Hean opens Changi Air Base (East)|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/MINDEF_20041129001_2.pdf|publisher=NAS|accessdate=13 August 2019|date=29 November 2004}}</ref>\n* 30 November - [[Temasek Holdings]] acquires HDB Corp (present-day [[Surbana Jurong]]) as part of [[Housing and Development Board]]'s divestment, allowing it to expand overseas to new markets in Asia. Likewise, entry barriers for private companies will be lifted from July 2006 with HDB Corp allowed access into private sector projects from 2007 onwards.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sale of HDB Corp to Temasek Holdings |url=https://www.temasek.com.sg/en/news-and-views/news-room/news/2004/sale-of-hdb-corp-to-temasek-holdings.html |website=Temasek Holdings |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=30 November 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=A Paulo |first1=Derrick |title=Temasek buys shareholding of HDB Corp |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20041201-2.2.5.3 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=1 December 2004}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n*4 December - The [[Nicoll Highway]] reopens to traffic, months after the [[Nicoll Highway collapse|collapse]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20041205.2.5.8 |title=Nicoll Highway opens after $3m in repairs |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |access-date=8 November 2019 |date=5 December 2004}}</ref>\n*6 December - The [[Media Development Authority]] (MDA) approves the [[Singapore media merger of 2004|merger]] involving both [[MediaCorp]]' and [[Singapore Press Holdings]]' [[free-to-air]] [[television]] operations, first announced in September.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www2.imda.gov.sg/news-and-events/Media-Room/archived/mda/Media-Releases/2004/mediacorp-sph-application-to-merge-massmarket-television-operations-approved |title=Mediacorp, SPH Application To Merge Mass-Market Television Operations Approved |website=MDA (now IMDA) |access-date=28 August 2019 |date=6 December 2004}}</ref>\n*29 December - The Boon Lay Extension of the [[East West MRT line]] is announced. The {{Convert|3.8|km|miles|abbr=in}} extension will be finished by 2009, with 2 elevated stations to be built.<ref>{{cite web |title=Expanding The Rail Network: LTA To Build Boon Lay MRT Extension |url=http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=1138 |publisher=LTA |accessdate=30 August 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070728180438/http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=1138 |archivedate=28 July 2007 |date=29 December 2004}}</ref>\n*31 December - \n**[[MediaCorp]] and [[Singapore Press Holdings]] (SPH) complete their [[Singapore media merger of 2004|merger]], creating the new holding company [[MediaCorp TV]]. [[Channel i (Singapore)|Channel i]] ceased transmission the following day, while [[Channel U (Singapore)|Channel U]] joined MediaCorp. In addition, [[Streats]] prints its last issue, merging into [[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]] the next day.<ref>{{cite web |title=MediaCorp and Singapore Press Holdings complete TV and free newspaper merger |url=http://www.corporate.mediacorp.sg/press_release/pr_1104473164.htm |accessdate=22 September 2019 |website=MediaCorp, SPH |date=31 December 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080122035743/http://www.corporate.mediacorp.sg/press_release/pr_1104473164.htm |archivedate=22 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sph.com.sg/media_releases/163 |title=Channel i to close on 1 January 2005 Channel U and Channel 8 to have complementary programming |website=MediaCorp, SPH |access-date=5 August 2019 |date=7 December 2004}}</ref>\n**Radio station [[Lush 99.5FM]] starts transmission.<ref>{{cite web |title=MediaCorp Radio launches new music station Lush 99.5FM |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/124905/1/.html |website=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=11 December 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050413211446/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/124905/1/.html |archivedate=13 April 2005 |date=30 December 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\n* 21 February - [[Khoo Teck Puat]] - Banker and hotel owner (b. 1917).<ref>{{cite web |title=Khoo Teck Puat |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1856_2011-11-16.html |website=NLB |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 1 June - [[Liu Kang (artist)|Liu Kang]] - Artist (b. 1911).<ref>{{cite web |title=Liu Kang |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_158_2005-01-22.html |website=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 6 August - [[Lien Ying Chow]] - Founder of [[Overseas Union Bank]] (b. 1906).<ref>{{cite web |title=Banker Lien Ying Chow dies, aged 98 |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20040807-1.2.8.1 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=7 August 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=George Lien Ying Chow |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1786_2011-02-24.html |website=NLB |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 29 August - [[Lin Chen (playwright)|Lin Chen]] - Theatre director and playwright (b. 1919).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lin Chen |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2014-02-10_162644.html |website=NLB |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 16 November - [[Goh Sin Tub]] - Writer (b. 1927).<ref>{{cite web |title=Goh Sin Tub |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_451__2008-11-11.html |website=NLB |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n* 7 December - Cheng Yik Hung - Founder of Wing Tai Group (b. 1911).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tay |first1=Tsen-Waye |title=Wing Tai Group founder Cheng Yik Hung dies at 93 |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20041208-1.2.31.4 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=8 December 2019 |date=8 December 2004}}</ref>\n* [[Christopher Henry Rothwell Allen]] - Actor, director, winner of 1983 [[Cultural Medallion]] for Theatre (b. 1933).<ref>{{cite web |title=Christopher Henry Rothwell Allen |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2014-01-10_175824.html |website=NLB |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Asia topic|2004 in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2004 In Singapore}}\n[[Category:2004 in Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{Dynamic list}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Year in Singapore|2004}}\n\nThe following lists events that happened during '''[[2004]] in [[Singapore]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[President of Singapore|President]]: [[S.R. Nathan]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Obituary: Sellapan Ramanathan (SR Nathan), statesman|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/obituary-sellapan-ramanathan-sr-nathan-statesman-1-4225292|website=Scotsman|accessdate=29 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]]: [[Goh Chok Tong]] (until 12 August), [[Lee Hsien Loong]] (starting 12 August)<ref name=nas>{{cite web|title=Changeover of Prime Minister: President's Office Press Statement, 10August 2004|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=2004081001.htm|website=www.nas.gov.sg|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n*1 January - The [[Goods and Services Tax (Singapore)|Goods and Services Tax]] is raised from 4% to 5%.<ref>{{cite web |title=Introduction of the Goods and Services Tax |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/c5594d45-4948-4080-a6fb-5175eb8d83c3 |publisher=NLB |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n*3 January - The [[Millennia Institute]] is established from a merger of other Centralised Institutes.\n*8 January - The [[Infocomm Development Authority of Singapore]] announced that phone numbers starting with '8' will become available from April after high demand for phone numbers starting with '9'.<ref>{{cite web |title=10 million mobile nos with prefix '8' launch |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20040109-1.2.6.6 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=10 September 2019 |date=9 January 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Supercharging Singapore: The 2000s|url=https://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/2015/10/35-years-of-ict/supercharging-singapore/the-2000s.html|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*3 February - The Braddell Flyover is opened to traffic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Braddell Flyover opens today (Page 3) |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes20040203-1.1.19 |publisher=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=3 February 2004}}</ref>\n*12 February - The [[Carlsberg Sky Tower]] (renamed to Tiger Sky Tower) is opened.\n*22 February - Plans for a new hospital in Jurong were postponed in favour for one in the north. These plans were elaborated on 22 March, when the [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Health Ministry]] announced a Northern General Hospital (now [[Khoo Teck Puat Hospital]]) in Yishun.<ref>{{cite web |title=Next new hospital to be in the north |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes20040223-1.1.6 |publisher=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=23 February 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=400-bed hospital for the north in Yishun Central |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/straitstimes20040323-1.1.4 |publisher=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=23 March 2004}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n*9 March - The [[Singapore Tourism Board]] launched a new tourism campaign called Uniquely Singapore.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Uniquely Singapore\" tourism campaign is launched|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/a016f18a-d260-4078-913d-93b58528b87f#1|website=NLB|accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref> \n*13 March - A new pre-tertiary arts school (now [[School of the Arts, Singapore|School of the Arts]]) is announced during a parliamentary debate to cater for students between the ages of 13 to 18.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ministerial Statement by Minister Lee Boon Yang in Parliament: Announcement on The Arts School |url=https://www.mci.gov.sg/pressroom/news-and-stories/pressroom/2004/3/ministerial-statement-by-minister-lee-boon-yang-in-parliamentannouncement-on-the-arts-school |website=MITA (now MCI) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=13 March 2004}}</ref> \n*17 March - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced more flexibility for school admissions and an all-rounded school ranking system.<ref>{{cite web |title=Greater flexibility in the school admission system |url=http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040317b.htm |website=MOE |accessdate=23 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308131150/http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040317b.htm |archivedate=8 March 2013 |date=17 March 2004 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=A more broad-based school ranking system |url=http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040317a.htm |website=MOE |accessdate=23 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308131557/http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040317a.htm |archivedate=8 March 2013 |date=17 March 2004 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*18 March - \n**The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced that the EM1 and EM2 streams will be merged.<ref>{{cite web |title=Refinements to primary school streaming |url=http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040318.htm |website=MOE |accessdate=23 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308131114/http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040318.htm |archivedate=8 March 2013 |date=18 March 2004 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n**The [[chewing gum ban in Singapore|chewing gum ban]] is partially lifted with the launch of [[Nicorette]], a smoking cessation gum.<ref>{{cite news |title=12-year chewing gum ban partially lifted |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20040317-2.2.13.5 |accessdate=23 August 2019 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |date=17 March 2004}}</ref>\n*26 March - [[The Arts House]] is opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening of The Arts House |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/39c23dc2-b6b6-416e-814b-ba558864bce5 |website=NLB |accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n*23 March - The [[Immigration and Checkpoints Authority]]'s Coastal Command Headquarters on [[Pulau Brani]] is officially opened by then [[Ministry of Home Affairs (Singapore)|Minister for Home Affairs]] [[Wong Kan Seng]].\n*29 March - The [[Media censorship in Singapore|M18 and R21 ratings]] are introduced, among other changes.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Film Rating System Offers More Viewing Choices |url=https://www2.imda.gov.sg/news-and-events/Media-Room/archived/mda/Media-Releases/2004/new-film-rating-system-offers-more-viewing-choices |website=MDA (now IMDA) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=22 March 2004}}</ref>\n*31 March - The [[Old National Library Building]] at Fort Canning is closed for the building of [[Fort Canning Tunnel]].\n\n===April===\n*1 April - \n**Two statutory boards, the [[Accounting and Corporate Regulatory Authority]] and [[Singapore Examinations and Assessment Board]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Formation of Singapore Examinations & Assessment Board|url=http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040331.htm |website=MOE |date=31 March 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025204603/http://moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040331.htm |archivedate=25 October 2012}}</ref> are formed.\n**All hawker centres are now managed by the [[National Environment Agency]], taking over roles previously held by the [[Housing and Development Board]] and [[JTC Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hawker centres |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1637_2010-01-31.html |website=NLB |accessdate=6 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 2 April - The [[Singapore Sports School]] is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening of the Singapore Sports School |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=2004040202.htm |website=NAS |accessdate=28 July 2019 |date=2 April 2004}}</ref>\n* 20 April \u2013 A section of [[Nicoll Highway]] [[Nicoll Highway collapse|collapsed]], four workers were killed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Loh |first1=Sharon |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20040421.2.2 |title=MRT worksite collapse wrecks Nicoll Highway |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |access-date=8 November 2019 |date=21 April 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Friday\u2019s fatal mishap among worst worksite accidents since 2004 Nicoll Highway tragedy|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/fridays-fatal-mishap-worst-worksite-accident-2004-nicoll-highway-tragedy|website=TODAYonline|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n*1 May - \n**The [[National Trades Union Congress]]'s new headquarters, [[One Marina Boulevard]] is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening of One Marina Boulevard |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=2004050101.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=22 August 2019 |date=1 April 2004}}</ref>\n**[[Singapore Pools]] is transferred to the [[Singapore Totalisator Board]]; present-day Tote Board (a statutory board of the [[Ministry of Finance (Singapore)|Ministry of Finance]]), taking over this role from [[Temasek Holdings]].\n*4 May - \n**The first $10 polymer notes are released.<ref>{{cite web|title=MAS Issues $10 Polymer Portrait Notes|url=https://www.mas.gov.sg/news/media-releases/2004/mas-issues-10dollar-polymer-portrait-notes|website=MAS|accessdate=15 July 2019}}</ref>\n**[[Valuair]] launches its first flights.\n*14 May - The [[Media Development Authority]] (MDA) awards the 99.5FM frequency to [[MediaCorp]] under MediaCorp Radio. The new station, GROOVES 99.5FM (renamed [[Lush 99.5FM]]) will broadcast local music and arts programmes, as well as jazz and programmes by tertiary students. The station will start broadcasting by end 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.imda.gov.sg/news-and-events/Media-Room/archived/mda/Media-Releases/2004/mediacorp-radio-awarded-995fm-frequency-for-new-radio-station |title=MediaCorp Radio Awarded 99.5FM Frequency For New Radio Station |website=MDA (now IMDA) |date=14 May 2004 |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n*19 May \u2013 First Lieutenant Brandon Loo of the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force]] is killed when his F-16 jet crashed while on training from the [[Luke Air Force Base]] in [[Arizona]].\n*21 May - The [[Changi Naval Base]] was officially opened.\n*29 May - [[StarHub]] launches its new digital cable TV service.<ref>{{cite web |title=Digital Cable Launch of Starhub Cable Vision Ltd |url=https://www.mci.gov.sg/pressroom/news-and-stories/pressroom/2004/5/speech-by-minister-lee-boon-yang-at-the-digital-cable-launch-of-starhub-cable-vision-ltd-at-2d-ayer-rajah-crescent-aos-building |publisher=MITA (now MCI) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=29 May 2004}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n*1 June - Security guards are now deployed in [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|MRT]] stations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Security guards start MRT patrols |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20040601-1.2.8.4 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=2 May 2020 |date=1 June 2004}}</ref>\n*4 June - Hippo City Sightseeing bus in Singapore started operations.\n*5 June - [[Wild Wild Wet]], a [[water theme park]] opens to the public in [[NTUC Downtown East|Downtown East]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Wild Wild Wet opens in Downtown East|url=http://getforme.com/previous2004/previous200604_wildwildwetopensindowntowneast.htm|website=Get For Me (Singapore)|accessdate=8 August 2019}}</ref>\n*15 June - [[Ministry of Defence (Singapore)|MINDEF]] announced that [[National service in Singapore|National Service]] will be cut from 2.5 years to 2 years from the December 2004 batch.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ministerial Statement on Full-time National Service Duration|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/MINDEF_20040615002.pdf|website=NAS|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref> \n*18 June - The third [[NEWater]] plant opened in [[Seletar]]. It operated for seven years until its closure in 2011. \n*29 June - A power blackout occurred in Singapore, affecting about one-third residents of Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=Massive blackout hits many parts of Singapore |url=http://getforme.com/previous2004/previous300604_massiveblackouthitsmanypartsofsingapore.htm |website=Getforme Singapore |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=30 June 2004}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n*20 July - The National Security Secretariat was renamed to [[National Security Coordination Secretariat]] as part of an enhanced [[national security]] plan.\n\n===August===\n*12 August - [[Lee Hsien Loong]] was sworn as the third [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20040813-1.2.2 |title=Let us shape our future together |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |access-date=12 February 2020 |date=13 August 2004}}</ref>\n*22 August - Pro-family policies were introduced during the [[Singapore National Day Rally|National Day Rally]]. Among the measures include an enhanced [[Baby bonus#Singapore|Baby Bonus]] scheme, increased maternity leave, more childcare options, a five-day work week, among others. In addition, female civil servants can claim medical benefits for their dependant unmarried children below 18 year and spouses from 1 January 2005, as well as two-day childcare leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=2004082502.htm|title=New package of measures to support parenthood|website=NAS|accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=2004082596.htm|title=\nCivil Service moves ahead with changes to promote a pro-family environment and better work-life balance for civil servants|website=NAS|accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n* 2 September - The [[Media Development Authority]] allows the sale of [[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]], a women-oriented magazine, coming after a 22-year ban since 1982 on the grounds of nudity. However, the magazine will be shrink-wrapped with the label 'Unsuitable for the Young' to protect vulnerable consumers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.imda.gov.sg/news-and-events/Media-Room/archived/mda/Media-Releases/2004/cosmopolitan-to-be-available-from-this-month|title=Cosmopolitan to be available from this month|publisher=MDA (now IMDA)|access-date=28 August 2019|date=2 September 2004}}</ref>\n* 17 September - In a bid to stem losses, [[MediaCorp]] and [[Singapore Press Holdings]] (SPH) announced the [[Singapore media merger of 2004|merging]] of their media operations. A new holding company [[MediaCorp TV]] will be created with MediaCorp owning 80 percent and SPH holding the remaining 20 percent. In addition, MediaCorp Press will continue to be owned by MediaCorp; holding a 60 percent stake with 40 percent to be sold to SPH. [[Channel i (Singapore)|Channel i]] will be reviewed for commercial viability while [[Streats]] will be merged with [[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sph.com.sg/media_releases/150 |title=MediaCorp And Singapore Press Holdings Merge Their TV And Free Newspaper Operations |website=MediaCorp, SPH |access-date=5 August 2019 |date=17 September 2004}}</ref> \n* 23 September - [[VivoCity]], formerly known as the HarbourFront Mall, is unveiled, opening in December 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mapletree.com.sg/en/Media/News/2004/Sept/23092004-MapletreeUnveilsNewWaveRetail.aspx|title=Mapletree Unveils the New Wave Of Retail|publisher=Mapletree|access-date=29 July 2019|date=23 September 2004}}</ref>\n* 24 September - The [[Direct School Admission]] was announced, allowing Primary 6 and Secondary 4 students to be guaranteed a place in a [[Secondary education in Singapore|secondary school]] and [[Junior college (Singapore)|junior college]] of their choice respectively. The scheme took effect from the 2005 cohort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/PR24Sep04.pdf|title=\nDirect School Admission for Integrated Programme|publisher=NAS|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 26 September - Reviews were announced for education awards, new school achievement tables and the scrapping of rankings for IP schools and junior colleges.<ref>{{cite news |title=A Broader Picture of Schools' Performance in Academic and Non-Academic Domains |url=http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040924b.htm |accessdate=28 July 2019 |publisher=MOE |date=26 September 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423085655/http://www.moe.gov.sg/media/press/2004/pr20040924b.htm |archivedate=23 April 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 30 September - [[PSA International]] sells its stake in CWT, a logistics company.<ref>{{cite news |title=PSA to sell entire stake in logistics company CWT (Page 38) |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/today20041001-1.1.38 |accessdate=23 August 2019 |publisher=Today (retrieved from NLB) |date=1 October 2004}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n* 2 October - The [[Yellow Ribbon Project]] and Yellow Ribbon Fund are officially launched to give ex-convicts a second chance.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yellow Ribbon Project |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1402_2009-01-05.html |website=NLB |accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tie a yellow ribbon... |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20041004-1.2.51.11 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=4 October 2004}}</ref>\n* 29 October - The first units of [[The Sail @ Marina Bay]] are launched, which is jointly developed by City Developments Limited and AIG Global Real Estate.<ref>{{cite web |title=CDL Celebrates the Launch of The Sail @ Marina Bay With a Big Bang |url=http://ir.cdl.com.sg/static-files/079893ec-2c5b-463f-aaf1-47d11f7b82e2 |publisher=CDL |accessdate=23 August 2019 |date=29 October 2004}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n* 29 November - The [[Changi Air Base (East)]] is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web|title=RADM (NS) Teo Chee Hean opens Changi Air Base (East)|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/MINDEF_20041129001_2.pdf|publisher=NAS|accessdate=13 August 2019|date=29 November 2004}}</ref>\n* 30 November - [[Temasek Holdings]] acquires HDB Corp (present-day [[Surbana Jurong]]) as part of [[Housing and Development Board]]'s divestment, allowing it to expand overseas to new markets in Asia. Likewise, entry barriers for private companies will be lifted from July 2006 with HDB Corp allowed access into private sector projects from 2007 onwards.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sale of HDB Corp to Temasek Holdings |url=https://www.temasek.com.sg/en/news-and-views/news-room/news/2004/sale-of-hdb-corp-to-temasek-holdings.html |website=Temasek Holdings |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=30 November 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=A Paulo |first1=Derrick |title=Temasek buys shareholding of HDB Corp |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20041201-2.2.5.3 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=1 December 2004}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n*4 December - The [[Nicoll Highway]] reopens to traffic, months after the [[Nicoll Highway collapse|collapse]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20041205.2.5.8 |title=Nicoll Highway opens after $3m in repairs |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |access-date=8 November 2019 |date=5 December 2004}}</ref>\n*6 December - The [[Media Development Authority]] (MDA) approves the [[Singapore media merger of 2004|merger]] involving both [[MediaCorp]]' and [[Singapore Press Holdings]]' [[free-to-air]] [[television]] operations, first announced in September.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www2.imda.gov.sg/news-and-events/Media-Room/archived/mda/Media-Releases/2004/mediacorp-sph-application-to-merge-massmarket-television-operations-approved |title=Mediacorp, SPH Application To Merge Mass-Market Television Operations Approved |website=MDA (now IMDA) |access-date=28 August 2019 |date=6 December 2004}}</ref>\n*29 December - The Boon Lay Extension of the [[East West MRT line]] is announced. The {{Convert|3.8|km|miles|abbr=in}} extension will be finished by 2009, with 2 elevated stations to be built.<ref>{{cite web |title=Expanding The Rail Network: LTA To Build Boon Lay MRT Extension |url=http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=1138 |publisher=LTA |accessdate=30 August 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070728180438/http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=1138 |archivedate=28 July 2007 |date=29 December 2004}}</ref>\n*31 December - \n**[[MediaCorp]] and [[Singapore Press Holdings]] (SPH) complete their [[Singapore media merger of 2004|merger]], creating the new holding company [[MediaCorp TV]]. [[Channel i (Singapore)|Channel i]] ceased transmission the following day, while [[Channel U (Singapore)|Channel U]] joined MediaCorp. In addition, [[Streats]] prints its last issue, merging into [[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]] the next day.<ref>{{cite web |title=MediaCorp and Singapore Press Holdings complete TV and free newspaper merger |url=http://www.corporate.mediacorp.sg/press_release/pr_1104473164.htm |accessdate=22 September 2019 |website=MediaCorp, SPH |date=31 December 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080122035743/http://www.corporate.mediacorp.sg/press_release/pr_1104473164.htm |archivedate=22 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sph.com.sg/media_releases/163 |title=Channel i to close on 1 January 2005 Channel U and Channel 8 to have complementary programming |website=MediaCorp, SPH |access-date=5 August 2019 |date=7 December 2004}}</ref>\n**Radio station [[Lush 99.5FM]] starts transmission.<ref>{{cite web |title=MediaCorp Radio launches new music station Lush 99.5FM |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/124905/1/.html |website=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=11 December 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050413211446/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/124905/1/.html |archivedate=13 April 2005 |date=30 December 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\n* 21 February - [[Khoo Teck Puat]] - Banker and hotel owner (b. 1917).<ref>{{cite web |title=Khoo Teck Puat |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1856_2011-11-16.html |website=NLB |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 1 June - [[Liu Kang (artist)|Liu Kang]] - Artist (b. 1911).<ref>{{cite web |title=Liu Kang |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_158_2005-01-22.html |website=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 6 August - [[Lien Ying Chow]] - Founder of [[Overseas Union Bank]] (b. 1906).<ref>{{cite web |title=Banker Lien Ying Chow dies, aged 98 |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20040807-1.2.8.1 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=7 August 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=George Lien Ying Chow |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1786_2011-02-24.html |website=NLB |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 29 August - [[Lin Chen (playwright)|Lin Chen]] - Theatre director and playwright (b. 1919).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lin Chen |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2014-02-10_162644.html |website=NLB |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 16 November - [[Goh Sin Tub]] - Writer (b. 1927).<ref>{{cite web |title=Goh Sin Tub |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_451__2008-11-11.html |website=NLB |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n* 7 December - Cheng Yik Hung - Founder of Wing Tai Group (b. 1911).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tay |first1=Tsen-Waye |title=Wing Tai Group founder Cheng Yik Hung dies at 93 |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20041208-1.2.31.4 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=8 December 2019 |date=8 December 2004}}</ref>\n* [[Christopher Henry Rothwell Allen]] - Actor, director, winner of 1983 [[Cultural Medallion]] for Theatre (b. 1933).<ref>{{cite web |title=Christopher Henry Rothwell Allen |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2014-01-10_175824.html |website=NLB |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Asia topic|2004 in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2004 In Singapore}}\n[[Category:2004 in Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "TheGreatSG'rean", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJune", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2004_in_Singapore"}
